description: Scary cat

The empty shell of a Hooked Slipper Snail (Crepidula adunca), photographed at Mavericks Beach in El Granada, CA.  The boat-like structure of this shell inidicates that it belongs to Slipper Snail genus (Crepidula), which has several native and introduced species in the San Francisco Bay Area.  The dark purplish-brown color, the high arch to its body, and the hooked, downward-pointing "beak" indicated that it is a Hooked Slipper Snail (Crepidula adunca), a native species frequently seen intertidally within our local tide pools.  This particular specimen is about 1.2 cm long X 8 mm wide X 7 mm high.
tag_list: Crepidula adunca, El Granada, Hooked Slipper Snail, Mavericks Beach, Pillar Point Headland, Rank 2, San Mateo County

description: The empty shell of a Black Tegula (Tegula funebralis), photographed at Mavericks Beach in El Granada, CA (coastal San Mateo County).  Both apical and apertural views provided.   In the apertural view, note that the outer lip of the shell's aperture has been broken off, so the aperture appears to be larger than it was when the shell's owner was alive.
tag_list: Black Tegula, El Granada, Mavericks Beach, Rank 1.5, San Mateo County, Tegula funebralis

description:
The empty shell of a Brown Tegula (Tegula brunnea), photographed at Mavericks Beach (the beach below the Pillar Point headland) in El Granada, San Mateo County, CA.  Both apical and apertural views are  provided.  Fom both of these views, note how heavy and clunky this shell is, with an overall conical shape that is almost (but not quite) as high as it is wide at the base.  The whorls of the shell are smoothe and undecorated, with a tightly set suture separating one whorl from the next.  The orange-brown color of this shell is fairly typical of the species.

From the apertural view, one can observe how thick the walls of this shell are.  Also observe how the shell's columella terminates in a single knobby tooth along the inner surface of the aperture; this tooth is apparently diagnostic, though T. brunnea differs so much from the other Tegula species in California that I've never needed to rely on it as a field mark.
tag_list: Brown Tegula, El Granada, Mavericks Beach, Pillar Point Headland, San Mateo County, Tegula brunnea

description:
Day 5 of one of the greatest vacations ever! Full journal of nature adventures here: http://www.inaturalist.org/journal/sambiology/9891-vacation-in-california-news-flash-i-like-california

Using the great existing observations from the San Francisco Bay area and species guide to help with the ID's -- but please correct me if I've goofed. Almost ALL of these organisms were new for me!

Elizabeth and I walked around Shollenberger Park in Petaluma (before the fabric stores opened up!).  This is a great park for birding -- lots of neat things we saw.

Just a couple of these bushes along the dirt road. Looks like there are no thorns on the branches and lots of prickles on the berries. The glabrous leaf shape matched this species and it's growing in the right place.
Looks like the flowers have dark blue pollen on their stamens, but I can't find any matching Gilia. Just one patch along fire road.

A couple scattered groups of these plants on bank of the road cut with partial western sun. The species name is just a guess. I couldn't find a description of the difference between P. clevelandii and this one. The photos of the leaves on P. h. look more with this group's leaves.
New leaves on Quercus kelloggii are spectacularly beautiful red-orange.
Dinosaur tracks coming from the pond created by a tiny stream flooding the dirt road. Someone from our campsite identified the dinosaur tracks in the photos later.
I only found a few places where these acorns had fallen onto the dirt road I was walking down. I couldn't get a good camera shot of the trees they were growing on.
Tiny pink mallow flowers in on small patch along dirt road.
The leaves on this one don't look as blue, and the flower pedicels don't looks the same shade of pink as the previous upload.
Arctistaphylos with blue-grey leaves and inflorescence with pink pedicels.
Growing under oaks along dirt road margin. All the mushrooms were somewhat dried up.

description:
The so-far undescribed species. 

From Jeff Goddard: 

"Cumanotus sp. 
Following Behrens (1991), Goddard (2004) referred to this species, which feeds on Ectopleura crocea (Agassiz, 1862) in bays and harbors, as Cumanotus fernaldi Thompson & Brown, 1984. However, as pointed out by S. Millen personal communication to JG, 8 Jan 2012), Thompson and Brown (1984) in their brief description of C. fernaldi were referring to the larger, soft-sediment dwelling species studied by Hurst (1967) that is ecologically and morphologically similar to the north Atlantic C. beaumonti (Eliot, 1906). Hurst (1967) used the name C. beaumonti for her specimens from Washington and reported that they laid corkscrew shaped egg masses with 414 eggs per egg capsule. Cumanotus sp. consistently has one egg per capsule (Goddard 1992; present study, Table 2), is ecologically and morphologically similar to the north Atlantic C. cuenoti Pruvot-Fol, 1948, and is undescribed (S. Millen, personal communication to JG, 8 Jan 2012). It is pictured as C. fernaldi in Behrens and Hermosillo (2005, species number 244), but that name actually applies to species number 245 in Behrens and Hermosillo (2005) (S. Millen, personal communication to JG, 8 Jan 2012). 
Unaware that two species of Cumanotus exist in the northeast Pacific Ocean, Goddard (2004, Table 1) lumped development data for both species. The complete and correct breakdown is as follows. Based on Hurst (1967), C. fernaldi (as C. beaumonti) deposits corkscrew-shaped egg masses with 414 eggs per capsule that hatch after 10 days at 811 C with type 1 shells averaging 119 mm long. Based on Goddard (1992, 2011b) and the present study, Cumanotus sp. also deposits corkscrew-shaped egg masses, but with one egg (averaging 73 mm in diameter) per capsule, hatching after 910 days at 1216 C with type 1 shells averaging 130 mm long."
